      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "053a8342e80f888e",
        "text": "Radical Constructivism aligns with Pragmatism in its instrumentalist approach, but changes the understanding of ‘truth’ to experiential ‘viability’. This use of the word ‘viability’ matches exactly that of Beer’s use in the development and use of the Viable System Model. A mental model is viable if it stands the test of experience. I interpret what James means by “world formula” as the set of mental models in use at any one time, and “true one” as the viable model in the sense defined by Von Glasersfeld. Hence, I conclude that with the foundation of Pragmatism, originating with Peirce, through to von Glasersfeld’s Radical Constructivism there is a coherent logical foundation for systemic process thinking, which replaces the reliance on ‘reality’ in the underpinning of WEIRD thinking. Importantly within this way of thinking about thinking it must be remembered that each individual is unique and understands the world in a unique way. They have a unique perspective on any situation the evidence for which comes from Checkland’s experience of the failure of the WEIRD approach in complex management situations."
